Anonymous Mon 02 Mar 2020 13:06:51 No.28704395 Report
Quoted By: >>28704827
>>28703833
Just describe what you would draw in writing. And also use Jon truby's 22 steps for the actual planning of the story. (or 7 steps, its shorter cousin) If you want a copy to the book, just ask. I have a pdf.
Here's the method I came up with:
I describe how many panels the page has. Then describe the flow. The flow is the gesture that I want my reader's eyes to follow. If I have a Z shaped flow, then I want to compose the panels so that the reader looks to the right, then diagonally across the middle panels to the bottom left corner and back t othe right. This is also called the "Line of sight"
Remember there are plenty of tools at your disposal for panelling to convey certain things. The larger the panel, the more time occurs in it and thus the more impact it will have on the reader. Likewise, the larger a border between a panels, the more time has passed between whats occured in both panels. Finally, you can use your sound affects as a guide, like in this page from a Loka comic I started a while back.
Here's the script I wrote for it:
>PAGE 3 (divided into three parts)
>TOP we see the bridge leading to the dormitories and the gate only its closed. A banner hangs over it but its still silhouetted. In front is a monster guard talking to a phone. “A nightguard! Ten years head professor of the school of scaring, and the moment the economy changes, they make me a night guard!”
>MIDDLE a little light shines across the left side of the bridge; the banner above the sign says “Gone (but) n (ot) forgotten (!). Loka’s tail is visible. The whine of the bus stops and becomes the thud thud thud. ‘Union’s on their side! They said I’m lucky! Fear tech fired their entire scaring staff!”
>BOTTOM. More light shines across the banner whiel loka’s tail is gone. Creak of the bus doors opening. “Sorry momma. I didn’ tmean to raise my voice.”
I didn't write down the line of sight, but you can still see one.

The square-cube law states that "When an object undergoes a proportional increase in size, its new surface area is proportional to the square of the multiplier and its new volume is proportional to the cube of the multiplier."

Lapras at a little over 8 foot is roughly 160% the height of the average woman at a little over 5 foot. If we consider that a woman can be thin but with nice curves around 120lbs, this means that if we keep the proportions the same but scale up the size so our lady is just over 8 foot tall, this lady would be 120*(1.6^3), or a bit over 490 pounds.

So if anything, 485 pounds is a little light for that lapras, especially once you consider that she's got a shell in addition to the regular human anatomy, and therefore would almost certainly weigh more than a similarly proportioned human of the same size.
